Based on the search results, I found information about using `lockedAccess` and `executeTransaction` with actions in Premiere Pro's UXP API. Here's what I found:

## Premiere Pro UXP: lockedAccess and executeTransaction Action Example

### API Definition

The `executeTransaction` method takes a callback with a `compoundAction` parameter and an optional `undoString`: `executeTransaction(callback: (compoundAction: CompoundAction) => void, undoString?: string): boolean` - this executes an undoable transaction by passing a compound action.(no content)The `lockedAccess` method is defined as: `lockedAccess(callback: () => void): void` - this gets a read/upgrade locked access to the Project, and the project state will not change during the execution of the callback function. You can call `executeTransaction` while having locked access.

### Practical Example

Here's a working code example from the Adobe community showing how to use these methods together:

```javascript
const app = require("premierepro");

async function insertItem() {
    try {
        const project = await app.Project.getActiveProject();
        const rootItem = await project.getRootItem();
        const items = await rootItem.getItems();
        const mainSequence = await project.getActiveSequence();
        const seqEditor = await app.SequenceEditor.getEditor(mainSequence);
        const insertionTime = await app.TickTime.createWithSeconds(3);
        const onlyShiftInputTrack = true;

        var itemToInsert;
        for (let i = 0; i < items.length; i++) {
            if (items[i].name == "Iceberg.MOV") {
                itemToInsert = items[i];
                break;
            }
        }

        // Create & Execute the Insertion Action
        project.lockedAccess(() => {
            project.executeTransaction((compoundAction) => {
                const actInsertProjItem = seqEditor.createInsertProjectItemAction(
                    itemToInsert, 
                    insertionTime, 
                    0, 
                    0, 
                    onlyShiftInputTrack
                );
                compoundAction.addAction(actInsertProjItem);
            });
        });
    } catch (err) {
        console.error(err);
    }
}
```

Community members have confirmed that using `lockedAccess` and `executeTransaction` together resolves issues with action execution.

### Key Points

- An important difference between ExtendScript (and CEP) and UXP in Premiere is that all ExtendScript calls were synchronous and blocked the Premiere UI while executing. In UXP, method calls are asynchronous and do not block the UI thread.

- As of August 2025, only Premiere Pro BETA builds support UXP plugins. The Premiere Pro UXP API documentation is available at https://developer.adobe.com/premiere-pro/uxp/.

- As of November 2025, Premiere Pro has moved to extensibility based on UXP. ExtendScript-based integrations are still supported and plan to remain so through September 2026.


